Yup! Also, note that the test case above won't work, because even if the destructor was called before `Function`, the raw memory contents could still happen to be unchanged, so you wouldn't know which is the case just because the string is printed correctly.

Instead, you'd want to check when the destructor is called; here's how:

	#include <string>
	#include <iostream>

	struct Str : std::string
	{
		Str() : std::string("hello")
		{ std::cout << "Str()" << std::endl; }
		~Str() { std::cout << "~Str()" << std::endl; }
	};
	int print(char const *s) { std::cout << s << std::endl; return 0; }
	int main() { print(Str().c_str()) + print(Str().c_str()); }

The output shows that the destructors are called at the end of the statement.

	Str()
	hello
	Str()
	hello
	~Str()
	~Str()

