This line copies around ~60 MB of data from `model_nn` into the pipeline, which we should make some effort to avoid. For this performance reason, and also for the sake of clarity, I would suggest a little reorganization of this function.

In particular, the protocol buffer APIs are designed to facilitate a top-down approach to filling out a protobuf value. Note that in the original code, we began by allocating the highest level Model instance, and then filling in everything inside using calls to `mutable_*` or `add_*` as appropriate.

Similarly, I suspect this will be simpler if in the NMS case, we follow this outline:
```
CoreML::Specification::Model model_pipeline;
auto* model_nn = model_pipeline->mutable_pipeline->add_models();
// Populate *model_nn.
auto* model_nms = model_pipeline->mutable_pileine->add_models();
// Populate *model_nms
```

I would also really recommend breaking this down into helper functions, to keep things organized. Offhand, one for populating `model_nn` (which can be shared with the non-NMS case), and perhaps some functions for reducing duplication in setting the model inputs and outputs (since Pipeline models explicitly duplicate these).

