> Before, when `node_id` does not exist in `cluster_scheduling_resources_`, a `SchedulingResources` will be created. Now, only an empty `std::shared_ptr<SchedulingResources>` is created, so this can crash (found in a nightly test).
> 
> Either make sure `node_id` always exists in `cluster_scheduling_resources_`, or create a non-empty `std::shared_ptr<SchedulingResources>` before calling `SetAvailableResources()`?

Nice catch! Besides, I think only set available resources (`cluster_scheduling_resources_[node_id]->SetAvailableResources`) inside `GcsResourceManager::SetAvailableResources` is not enough, we should also check that if the node is already exist, if not then create a `SchedulingResources` which initialize both total and available resources.


```
void GcsResourceManager::SetAvailableResources(const NodeID &node_id,
                                               const ResourceSet &resources) {
  auto iter = cluster_scheduling_resources_.find(node_id);
  if (iter == cluster_scheduling_resources_.end()) {
    iter = cluster_scheduling_resources_
               .emplace(node_id, std::make_shared<SchedulingResources>(resources))
               .first;
  }
  iter->second->SetAvailableResources(ResourceSet(resources));
}
```

